    "texts": [
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Previous names",
            "shortText": "<p><i>Mactra spengleri</i>. Often misspelt <i>Schizodesma</i> in error</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_9_1085",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Identification features",
            "shortText": "<p>Large, almost triangular clam with a distinctive, almost-flat posterior end that is sharply delimited from the lateral section of the shell by an angular ridge. Outer surface with fine growth lines, off-white with broad darker brown zone around growing margins. Internally the ligamental pit at the hinge is deep and conspicuous. Siphons fused.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_1_1086",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Adult size",
            "shortText": "<p>Up to 113 mm shell length.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_2_1087",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Distribution",
            "shortText": "<p><u>Global:</u> Endemic to Southern Africa.</p><p><u>Local/Regional: </u>False Bay to East London.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_3_1088",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Biology",
            "shortText": "<p>Burrows in fine sediments from low water to about 8 m depth. Very common in False Bay, where it is often washed up in considerable numbers after storms, but uncommon elsewhere.&nbsp;</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_4_1089",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Food / prey",
            "shortText": "<p>Like almost all bivalves feeds by pumping water in via an inhalant siphon, filtering out fine particles though the enlarged gills and then ejecting the filtered water through an exhalent siphon.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_5_1090",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Reproduction",
            "shortText": "<p>Like almost all bivalves is a broadcast spawner. Details of reproductive cycle of this species have not been investigated.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_6_1091",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Similar species",
            "shortText": "<p>Adults unlikely to be confused with other regional species due to their large size and unusual squared-off posterior surface of the shell. Often found together with <i>Mactra glabrata,</i> but that species is fatter with a rounded, not squatted off, posterior end.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_7_1092",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Further reading / References",
            "shortText": "Branch, G, Griffiths, CL, Branch, M & Beckley, L (2016). Two Oceans: A Guide to the Marine Life of Southern Africa. (Fourth edition) Struik Nature, Cape Town. (p. 152).<br><br>Kilburn, R & Rippey, E (1982). Sea Shells of Southern Africa. Macmillan South Africa, Johannesburg (p. 179).<br><br>Signorelli, JH (2021). The Family Mactridae Lamarck, 1809 (Bivalvia: Cardiida) in South African Waters. <i>Malacologia</i>, 63(2), 195-223.",
